Strip LD_PRELOAD at script start, save it for NESTEDFIX re-injection.

scopebuddy 1.4.0 only unsets LD_PRELOAD inside the final `eval` line. Every
prior subshell — grep, perl, jq, wlr-randr, and the bash forks themselves —
inherits Steam's gameoverlayrenderer.so via LD_PRELOAD. The overlay lib
initializes inside those helpers, allocates IPC + futexes, then deadlocks in
__futex_wait — scopebuddy hangs forever before gamescope ever launches.

Fix: save LD_PRELOAD into __SCB_SAVED_LD_PRELOAD at the top of the script
and unset it immediately. SCB_NESTEDFIX still picks it up from the saved
variable and re-injects it for the game process via `env LD_PRELOAD=...`.

--- a/bin/scopebuddy
+++ b/bin/scopebuddy
@@ -1,4 +1,7 @@
 #!/usr/bin/env bash
+__SCB_SAVED_LD_PRELOAD="${LD_PRELOAD:-}"
+unset LD_PRELOAD
+export LD_PRELOAD=
 # Special thanks to @coolavery for the initial script for this
 # https://github.com/ValveSoftware/gamescope/issues/835#issuecomment-2496383830
 #
@@ -801,7 +804,7 @@
     # Apply nested gamescope fix for steam overlay and steam input
     if [ "$SCB_NESTEDFIX" -eq 1 ]; then
         # Transfer LD_PRELOAD before we unset it
-        LD_PRELOAD_REAL=$LD_PRELOAD
+        LD_PRELOAD_REAL=$__SCB_SAVED_LD_PRELOAD
     fi

     # Unset LD_PRELOAD for gamescope (as it breaks the overlay) then start gamescope with LD_PRELOAD set for %command% instead
